John Edward: Language skills are crucial to global citizens
Scotland's independent schools enjoy the reputation of academic excellence and this continued in 2018 with another set of outstanding exams, which are further strengthened by individual and collective success in sport, art, music and other community efforts.
With more than 30,000 pupils across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council for Independent Schools (SCIS), aim to provide the highest level of service for their pupils and their parents.
Independent schools want to prepare their pupils for further and higher education, the chosen career and the place they have as global citizens.
As a sector of education that can design and implement a tailor-made school programme, modern languages are still a popular and desirable subject in schools.
Nelson Mandela said: “If you talk to a person in a language that he understands, the conversation is memorable.
But if you talk to a man in his mother tongue, words are imprinted in his heart.”
This is a good reminder that we should not rely solely on English when we want to establish relations and trust with people from other countries.
This year's results of recent exams show that languages are at the top of the ranking with the highest performance levels in independent schools.
68 percent of students who learned a foreign language achieved excellent grades.
Data collected in 74 schools in the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) showed that 72 percent of pupils achieved excellent grades in Mandarin, with 72 percent of German students, 69 percent of French students and 63 percent of Spanish students.
This proves that schools of their own in Scotland support foreign languages as the key knowledge that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are treated in the same way as subjects in the fields of science, technology, engineering and mathematics as an optional subject in school curricula and elsewhere.
A survey carried out by the UK Employment and Training Commission in 2014 showed that 17 percent of the reasons why employers are struggling to fill vacancies can be attributed to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly necessary in preparing young people for their future careers.
For future job opportunities that require language skills, these skills are essential in the global world.
If a person learns another language, whatever career he chooses, with such lifelong knowledge, he has a great advantage in the future.
A multilingual person who can communicate directly with people from foreign countries automatically takes precedence over competition.
The 2013 YouTube survey of over 4,000 adults in the UK showed that 75 percent of people did not speak a foreign language well enough to be able to talk, and French was the only language spoken by two-digit percent of respondents, namely 15 percent.
Therefore, investing in language learning is important for children today.
With the knowledge of more languages, especially those from developing countries, children have a better chance of finding suitable employment.
In Scotland, schools differ in the languages they teach.
Many schools focus on more classical modern languages, while others teach languages that are considered to be the most important for the UK in 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of your child’s interest, it will always be possible to choose a number of languages taught by professionals in this field in independent schools.
Scotland's independent schools are committed to providing a learning environment that will prepare and equip children with the skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future holds.
In a global business environment, it cannot be denied that languages remain extremely important for the future of the country, so this must also be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should be seen as "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence for young people in Scotland.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
