North Korea: “Without trust, we will not disarm unilaterally”
On Saturday, the North Korean Foreign Minister informed the United Nations that the continued application of sanctions is causing increasing mistrust in the United States and that, under such conditions, North Korea will certainly not unilaterally renounce its nuclear weapons.
During the annual session of the General Assembly of this global body, Ri Jong Ho said that North Korea had taken a number of "significant measures in a good mood" over the past year, such as stopping nuclear and missile experiments, tearing down a city for nuclear experiments and promising not to spread nuclear weapons and technology.
“However, we do not see an adequate response from the United States,” he said.
"Without confidence in the United States, we will not be sure of national security, and under such conditions we will by no means be the first to disarm ourselves unilaterally."
While Ri repeated the known complaints made by North Korea regarding the resistance of Washington to a gradual approach to nuclear disarmament, in which North Korea would have been rewarded for taking gradual measures, his statement was important because it did not immediately reject unilateral nuclear disarmament, as Pyongyang had done in the past.
Ri took note of a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump from the first summit between the current president of the United States and the North Korean leader, which took place in Singapore on 12 June. At that time, Kim committed to working for the “nuclear disarmament of the Korean Peninsula”, while Trump promised security guarantees to North Korea.
North Korea wants the official conclusion of the Korean war, which took place between 1950 and 1953, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first give up nuclear weapons.
Washington has also not yielded to calls for the release of the strict international sanctions applicable to North Korea.
“The US insists on first nuclear disarmament and on increasing the pressure of sanctions in order to force us to achieve our goals and even oppose the declaration of the end of the war,” said Ri.
»The thought that sanctions could bring us to our knees is an unrealistic hope of those who do not know us at all.
The problem, however, is that the continued application of sanctions deepens our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention the plans for the second summit between Kim and Trump, which was highlighted by the U.S. President at the UN Assembly at the beginning of the week.
Instead, the Minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean President Mun Ja Ino, which took place over the past five months, and added: "If we had talked to South Korea about the problem of nuclear disarmament and not the US, the nuclear disarmament of the Korean peninsula would not have ended up at such a deadlock."
Nevertheless, the tone of the Rio speech was quite different from last year when he told the United Nations General Assembly that the attack on the continental part of the United States with North Korean missiles was inevitable, after “Mr. Evil President” Trump Kim was described as a “missile man” on a suicide mission.
This year, Trump, who threatened to "completely destroy" North Korea, commended Kim at the United Nations Assembly and his courage to take measures to disarm, but said that he still had a lot of work to do and that sanctions had to remain in force until North Korea was disarmed.
On Wednesday, Trump said that there was no time frame for this, stating: "It can take two years, three years or five months – it doesn't matter."
China and Russia believe that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures taken.
However, on Thursday, U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo said to the UN Security Council: “The enforcement of Security Council sanctions must proceed decisively without exception until the state of nuclear disarmament is fully, definitively and verified.”
Since 2006, the Security Council has unanimously adopted additional sanctions for North Korea to make it impossible to finance North Korean nuclear and ballistic missile programmes.
Pompeo met with Ri in the margins of the United Nations General Assembly and later said that Pyongyang would visit again next month to prepare for the second summit.
