Harvard University students attend a course where they learn how to take enough time to rest
The goal of this year's course at Harvard University is to teach all undergraduate students how to afford more sleep. They want to fight the growing macho culture of "full-night" learning, where they accumulate their powers with caffeine.
A university professor found that students of the world’s best university often do not know the basics of taking care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at the Brigham Women's Hospital, designed a course that he considered to be the first of its kind in the United States.
He decided to conduct such a course after his lecture on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
