Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and an executive director of the university’s medical services, says that they decided to take such a course when they found that students had a significant lack of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In one section there is a picture of the door of the student home, where students can click on coffee cups, curtains, sports shoes and books to obtain information about the impact of caffeine and light, the impact of lack of sleep on sports success and the importance of sleeping routine.
In the second section, participants learn that long-term sleep deprivation may increase the risk of cardiac arrest, stroke, depression and cancer.
A map of the student settlement with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We realize that student behavior will not change immediately.
