The professor says that the culture of pride is still present with the "overnight learning". He also adds that modern technology and increasing pressure on students, resulting in a lack of sleep, are a growing problem.
Professor Czeisler says that sufficient quality sleep should be a "secret weapon" for students to combat stress, exhaustion and anxiety. This can also avoid gaining weight – the brain becomes a form of hunger due to lack of sleep, making students constantly hungry.
A 19-year-old California student of chemical and physical biology Raymond So helped Professor Czeisler design the course. Last year, during his first year at Harvard, he attended one of the professors' lectures.
He says that the lecture opened his eyes and encouraged him to conduct the course throughout the campus.
He hopes that in the next phase he will be able to ask his post-graduate students to complete a similar study programme before entering the competition institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends students to set an alarm clock for sleep as well as waking up. He also wants to warn them about the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted by electronic displays and LED lighting, as they can cause an imbalance of circadian rhythm, making it difficult to sleep.
