HIV/AIDS: China reports a 14% increase in new cases
China has announced a 14% increase in the number of citizens living with HIV and AIDS.
Health officials say that more than 820,000 people in the country are affected.
In the second quarter of 2018, around 40,000 new cases were reported.
In the vast majority of new cases, the disease has been transmitted through sexual intercourse, which represents a change compared to the past.
Usually, HIV spread rapidly in some parts of China due to a transfusion of infected blood.
However, according to Chinese health officials at a conference in Junan Province, the number of people infected with HIV in this way has declined to almost zero.
However, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS continues to increase by 100,000 a year in China.
The transmission of HIV through sexual intercourse is a very pressing problem in the Chinese community of LGBT.
Homosexuality was decriminalised in China in 1997, but discrimination against people from the LGBT community is still very much present.
Since conservative values still apply in the country, 70-90% of men who have sex with men marry a woman over time.
The disease is often transmitted due to inadequate sexual protection in such relationships.
Since 2003, the Chinese Government has promised universal access to HIV medicines as part of its efforts to solve the problem.
