Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, is opening up a start-up company that will compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The last project of this technological legend, Inrupt, is a company building on Berners Open Source Platform Solid.
Solid allows users to choose where their data are stored and who has access to which information.
In an exclusive interview for Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that the intention of Inrupt was "to rule the world".
"We decided to do it now", he said about a new company.
"It's a historic moment."
The application uses Solid platform technology to enable users to create a "personal storage repository" or POD
This may include contact details, to-do lists, calendars, music library and other personal and professional tools.
It is similar as if Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify were all available in one browser and at the same time.
A special feature of a personal data storage repository is that the user can fully determine who can access what information.
The company calls it "personal empowerment with data".
Executive Director John Bruce says that the idea of a company is to pool resources, processes and appropriate skills that will allow access to the Solid platform for everyone.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, some hired developers to work on the project and a community of volunteer programmers.
Already this week technology developers around the world could create their own decentralised applications using the tools available on Inrupt’s website.
