In the study, scientists from the National Fund for Scotland (NTS) will accompany small bats and tiny bats and brown bats and bypass bats on the Inverewe Gardens estate in the Wester Ross area.
Special recorders will be set up to monitor bat activity throughout the season in key locations of the estate.
NHS personnel and volunteers will also conduct mobile research using manual detectors.
Professional audio analysis of all recordings will confirm the frequency of bat calls and what types of what they're doing.
They will then draw up a habitat map and a report to provide a detailed picture of their behavior throughout the landscape.
Rob Dewar, an NTS nature conservation consultant, hopes that the results will show which habitat areas are most suitable for bats and how each species uses them.
This information will help to identify the benefits of habitat management, such as the creation of meadows and the conservation of forests for bats and other related species.
The number of bat populations in Scotland and throughout the United Kingdom has decreased sharply in the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development work, which affects shelters and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting, as well as flytraps and some types of chemical treatment of building materials, as well as attacks by pets also pose a risk.
Bats aren't really blind.
Because of their night - to - night hunting habits, they use their ears rather than their eyes to catch their prey.
They use sophisticated echolocation techniques to accurately identify errors and obstacles along the flight path.
The NTS, responsible for supplying more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens, and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes bats very seriously.
