“We have an excellent area for bats in Thravo,” he said.
»We have old buildings, lots of ancient trees and all the quality habitat.
However, much is still known about bats, so the work we do here and on other properties will help us to understand better what they need to thrive.”
He stressed the importance of checking the presence of bats before carrying out maintenance work on holdings, since the possible accidental destruction of a single bat hospital could lead to the death of up to 400 females and puppies, which could result in the collapse of the entire local population.
Bats are protected, so it is forbidden to kill, harass or disturb them, and it is forbidden to destroy their maternity home.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish leader of the Bat Conservation Fund, encouraged the public to cooperate.
She said: "We still have much to learn about our bats, and for many species we simply do not know how well they stick to their populations."
