News of the Red Tide: Concentrations along the shores of the Pinellas, Manatee and Saratos districts are decreasing
The latest report by the Florida Fish and Game Protection Commission (FWC) shows a general decrease in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
The FWC reported more diffuse flowering in the areas of the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Saratos, Charlotte and Collier, indicating a decrease in concentrations.
The red tide stretches about 130 miles from the north coast of Pinellas County to the southern districts of Lee.
The patch looks about 10 miles from Hillsborough County, but in fewer places than last week.
Red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
In the past week, medium concentrations have been reported in the district of Pinellas and along its coast, low to high concentrations along the coast of Hillsborough, basic to high concentrations in the district of Manatee, basic to high concentrations in the district of Saratosa and along its coast, basic to medium concentrations in the district of Charlotte, basic to high concentrations in the county of Lee County and along its coast, and low concentrations in the district of Collier.
Respiratory irritation continues to be reported from the districts of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee, and Collier.
Respiratory irritation has not been reported in the past week from Northwest Florida.
